The panchromatic image usually only consists of the visible spectrum so much of the image detail is lost compared to multispectral images with resolutions in the same spectrum. By combining the two images and destroying edge detail, details that are not visible in the panchromatic image can be rendered visible. For higher resolution land imagery, a higher resolution panchromatic image is required. Multi-resolution land imagery is available from LANDSAT 8 and requires quad-band imaging to create. SWIR and NIR images combined with visible images create land images that may require pansharpening techniques.
